Here's the full migration. The code uses three `Thread.Abort`-dependent patterns that don't exist in modern .NET:

## Pattern Inventory

| Original Pattern | Problem in .NET 8 | Replacement |
|---|---|---|
| `Response.End()` | Called `Thread.Abort` internally → `PlatformNotSupportedException` | Just return from the action |
| `Response.Redirect(url, true)` | `endResponse=true` called `Thread.Abort` | Return `RedirectResult` |
| `catch (ThreadAbortException)` | Never thrown in .NET 8 — dead code | Remove entirely |

## Migrated Code (ASP.NET Core / .NET 8)

```csharp
using Microsoft.AspNetCore.Mvc;

public class ReportController : Controller
{
    // POST /report/export
    [HttpPost]
    public IActionResult Export()
    {
        var data = GenerateReport();

        // In ASP.NET Core, returning a result IS the response.
        // No Response.Clear/Write/End — just return a FileResult.
        return File(
            System.Text.Encoding.UTF8.GetBytes(data),
            "text/csv",
            "report.csv");
    }

    // POST /report/redirect
    [HttpPost]
    public IActionResult RedirectAction()
    {
        if (!User.Identity?.IsAuthenticated ?? true)
        {
            // Return a redirect result — no thread abort, no exception.
            return Redirect("/login");
        }

        try
        {
            ProcessRequest();
            return Redirect("/success");
        }
        // NOTE: catch (ThreadAbortException) block is removed entirely.
        // It was only needed because Response.Redirect(url, true) threw it.
        // In ASP.NET Core, Redirect() just returns a result object — no exception.
        catch (Exception ex)
        {
            LogError(ex);
            return Redirect("/error");
        }
    }

    private string GenerateReport() => /* ... */ "";
    private void ProcessRequest() { /* ... */ }
    private void LogError(Exception ex) { /* ... */ }
}
```

## Key Pitfalls

**1. Don't recreate `Response.End()` by writing directly to the response stream.**
```csharp
// ❌ WRONG — porting the old pattern literally
Response.Body.WriteAsync(bytes);
Response.CompleteAsync(); // NOT equivalent to Response.End()

// ✅ RIGHT — return a result object
return File(bytes, "text/csv", "report.csv");
```

**2. Don't catch `OperationCanceledException` as a blanket replacement for `ThreadAbortException`.**
The old `catch (ThreadAbortException)` was swallowing an *expected* framework side-effect. In ASP.NET Core there is no side-effect — just remove the catch. Only catch `OperationCanceledException` if you're using `CancellationToken` and have explicit recovery logic.

**3. Check `User.Identity` for null.** In ASP.NET Core, `User.Identity` can be null when no authentication middleware is configured. Use `?.IsAuthenticated ?? true` or similar.

**4. `Response.Redirect()` in ASP.NET Core does NOT throw.** It sets a 302 header. If you call it mid-method and keep executing, *all remaining code still runs*. Always `return Redirect(...)` to exit the action.

```csharp
// ❌ DANGEROUS — code after Redirect still executes
Response.Redirect("/login");
SensitiveOperation(); // THIS STILL RUNS!

// ✅ CORRECT — return exits the action
return Redirect("/login");
```

**5. For long-running exports, use `HttpContext.RequestAborted`** to cooperatively cancel if the client disconnects:
```csharp
[HttpPost]
public async Task<IActionResult> ExportLarge(CancellationToken cancellationToken)
{
    // ASP.NET Core automatically binds HttpContext.RequestAborted here
    var data = await GenerateLargeReportAsync(cancellationToken);
    return File(data, "text/csv", "report.csv");
}
```
